body:
@obrakmann: I wouldn't go that harsh with words over there, calling a probably good step in the right direction a bad one. https://github.com/OpenRA/ra2/issues/208 explains the reasons behind this PR (albeit I acknowledge and agree with declining it). The sole reason why thirdparty mods atm work is because all thirdparty modders deal with the release issues on their own and probably not try to automate a release (best example: @reaperrr compiled/uploaded a TDX release manually ffrom what I saw to GitHub).

The true solution to this problem would be (notsure how feasible this is, because I lack the required knowledge of .gitignore and makefiles) something like to make gitignoring a lot more explicit (ignore any mod folders which are not OpenRA-supported both in C# - since thirdparty libraries already follw the OpenRA naming convention with OpenRA.Mods.RA2/D2/AS/TDX - and within the mods, with only tracking cnc, d2k, modchooser, ra, and ts folder there) and somehow rewriting the makefile to be scripted to notice all additional all mod code projects without the c'n'p tricks it has to rely on atm.

If commits like https://github.com/GraionDilach/OpenRA/commit/97b0f450d4c82ddf0e933ce77c5e5139f2502af5 wouldn't be required to ensure automated compilation (NB: I'm not asking for the solution expansion nor the code check aspect) then the issues this PR meant to solve can be solved without upstream interference.

@Iamgoofball Please do not meddle into discussions you don't understand. Especially with such a tone. There aren't enough manpower to fully finish TS and D2k at the moment either, broadening the main project at this point is beyond the capacity. The RA2 project should stay third-party to decrease the wandering and let upstream concentrate to the upstream aims.

Besides that, RA2 is pledged with enough legal issues as-is already.

TLDR: You have no idea what you're talking about so it's better if you'd just drop the topic, thank you.
